Calls and display calls from several groups of birds swimming along the shoreline north of the point. Frog-like quacks (as at 2, 6, 10 seconds) given by the female, flicking her head up as she gave them. Reedy, overslurred calls given by the males, throwing their necks forward and popping their heads skyward at the last second, often as they approached a female, and often while noisily splashing themselves through the water towards her and other males.
NOTES: 4 birds take off from water.Also: calls from Bonaparte's Gull, and identificationQ 1-2.

mediaNotes: One bird called twice near the beginning of the recording.

Squeaky display calls from several males as they performed courtship displays for several females, bowing forward in the water then raising their heads up. A few low, quacking female calls as well. At 3:11, the whole flock takes off, perhaps due to my movement or to an approaching boat. Background: Herring Gull, traffics, waves lapping on breakwall.
